Sure! Here's the updated HTML code that makes "Hello, World!" appear front and center, and adds a button that changes the text color randomly:


```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Hello, World!</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
    </center>
    <div align="center">
      <button onclick="randomColor()">Random Color</button>
    </div>
    <script>
      function randomColor() {
        var colors = ["red", "green", "blue", "yellow"];
        var randomColor = colors[Math.floor(Math.random() * 4)];
        document.getElementById("color-text").style.color = randomColor;
      }
      function randomColor() {
        var colors = ["red", "green", "blue", "yellow"];
        var randomColor = colors[Math.floor(Math.random() * 4)];
        document.getElementById("color-text").innerHTML = randomColor;
      }
    </script>
  </body>
</html>

```

In this code, the `` <h1> `` element is centered using the `` center `` CSS property, and the `` <div> `` element is centered using the `` align="center" `` CSS property. The button "Random Color" is added using the `` onclick `` attribute, and when it is clicked, the function `` randomColor() `` is called. The `` randomColor() `` function first selects 4 random colors from an array of colors (red, green, blue, yellow), and then sets the background color of the element with the ID "color-text" to a random color. The second `` randomColor() `` function also selects 4 random colors, but then sets the text content of the element with the ID "color-text" to a random color.

